y and the line \"this life of living on the road\" suggest over-the-road trucking. At the start of the song he's hauling logs off a mountain and at the end he may be weighing options: \"rolling in\" to home base for a new cargo or seeing his Bessie again.\n\nRobertson has said of the song:{{quote|We're not dealing with people at the top of the ladder, we're saying what about that house out there in the middle of that field? What does this guy think, with that one light on upstairs, and that truck parked out there? That's who I'm curious about. What is going on in there? And just following the story of this person, and he just drives these trucks across the whole country, and he knows these characters that he drops in on, on his travels. Just following him with a camera is really what this song's all about.<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|title=Up on Cripple Creek|author=Janovitz, B.|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/up-on-cripple-creek-mt0011252707|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref>}}\n\n[[AllMusic]] critic Bill Janovitz describes the [[melody]] as \"light and catchy,\" also stating that the song has a \"New Orleans [[groove (music)|groove]].\"<ref name=allmusic/> Janovitz also regards the \"non-traditional, funky style\" of [[Garth Hudson]]'s [[clavinet]] playing a precursor of [[Stevie Wonder]]'s similar keyboard playing on \"[[Superstition (song)|Superstition]].\"<ref name=allmusic/>\n\nThe [[hip hop]] duo [[Gang Starr]] sampled the rhythm track on their own song \"Beyond Comprehension.\"<ref name=allmusic/>\n\n==Chart performance==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1969-70)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian ''RPM'' Singles Chart\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100\n|align=\"center\"|25\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Levon Helm]] \u2013 lead vocals, drums\n*[[Rick Danko]] \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals\n*[[Garth Hudson]] \u2013 [[clavinet]] with [[wah-wah pedal]], [[Lowrey organ]]\n*[[Richard Manuel]] \u2013 piano, backing vocals\n*[[Robbie Robertson]] \u2013 electric guitar\n\n== In popular culture ==\n* The song played into the credits of episode 11 of the second season of ''[[The Last Man on Earth (TV series)|The Last Man on Earth]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/mike-miller-returns-earth-solid-last-man-earth-233319|title = Mike Miller returns to Earth on a solid The Last Man On Earth|website = www.avclub.com|access-date = 2016-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==Recorded covers==\n*[[The Oak Ridge Boys]], on their 1982 album ''[[Bobbie Sue]]''\n*[[Tom Wopat]], on the 1979 ''[[The Dukes of Hazzard]]'' [[Television program|TV show]] [[soundtrack]]\n*[[Gomez (band)|Gomez]], on the 2007 Band tribute album ''[[Endless Highway: The Music of The Band]]''\n*Farmboy, on the 2003 album ''Farmboy''\n*[[Apollo Sunshine]], on the 2005 album ''Live at the Paradise''\n*[[Chadwick Stokes Urmston]], on the 2011 album ''Live at the Armory''\n*[[Blackberry Smoke]] with [[Bob Weir]], on the 2017 DVD ''An Evening At TRI''\n*[[Jack DeJohnette]]'s quartet, on their 2017 album ''[[Hudson (album)|Hudson]]''\n*[[Jason Manns]] feat. [[Jensen Ackles]], [[Mark Pellegrino]], [[Rob Benedict]] & [[Richard Speight Jr.]] on Jason Manns' album [[Recovering with Friends]] 2018.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|band|up-on-cripple-creek}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{The Band}}\n\n[[Category:The Band songs|Up on Cripple Creek]]\n[[Category:1969 songs|Up on Cripple Creek]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Robbie Robertson]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by John Simon (record producer)]]\n[[Category:1969 singles]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed # to No.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Up_on_Cripple_Creek"}
{"title_page": "Etika", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Etika\n| image              = Etika in 2019 - 2.jpg\n| caption            = Etika in May 2019\n| birth_name         = Desmond Daniel Amofah\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1990|5|12}}\n| birth_place        = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]], U.S.\n| nationality        = [[Americans|American]]\n| height             = {{convert|6|ft|6|in|m}}<ref>{{cite web | url = https://heavy.com/entertainment/2018/10/etika/ | title = Is Etika OK? YouTuber Writes \u2018It\u2019s My Turn to Die\u2019 on Reddit | first = Paul | last=  Farrell | date = October 26, 2018 | accessdate = March 5, 2020 | work = [[Heavy (website)|Heavy]] }}</ref>\n| other_names        = {{ubl|Iceman}}\n| occupation         = {{Flatlist|\n*[[YouTuber]]\n*[[Online streamer|streamer]]\n*[[Model (person)|model]]\n}}\n| years_active       = 2011\u20132015 (model)<br/>2012\u20132019 (YouTuber)\n| death_date         = {{circa|{{Death date and age|2019|06|19|1990|5|12}}|lk=yes|i=yes}}\n| death_cause        = [[Suicide methods#Drowning|Suicide by drowning]]\n| death_place        = [[Manhattan]], New York, U.S.\n| parents            = {{plainlist|\n*[[Owuraku Amofah]] (father)\n*Sabrina Amofah (mother)\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|etikaworldnetwork.com}}\n| module             = {{Infobox YouTube personality\n| embed = yes\n| channels       = {{ubl|[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCh0SxnImUvpWs_ZfEoyhkMA EWNetwork] (terminated)|[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC8Fd7MyCATxj4PvDjgHC9rg EtikaFRFX] (terminated)|[https://www.youtube.com/user/Tr1Iceman TR1Iceman]|[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCeVmD7fCjUo5Nqk35zcF6Og E Live]}}\n| years_active         = 2012\u20132019\n| catchphrase(s)       = {{ubl|\"What's going on guys? Etika, from the Etika World Network here.\"|\"Take care of yourselves, and of course, as usual, please have yourself a damn good one.\"}}\n| genre             = {{flatlist|\n* [[Let's Play]]\n* [[Reaction_video|react]]\n* [[vlog]]\n* [[comedy]]\n}}\n| subscribers          = 1.3 million (combined)\n| subscriber_date      = \n| views                = 145 million (combined)\n| view_date            = \n| network              = \n| associated_acts      = \n| silver_button        = yes \n| silver_year          = 2015{{efn|Amofah passed 100,000 subscribers on three channels; EWNetwork in 2015, EtikaFRFX in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/channel/UC8Fd7MyCATxj4PvDjgHC9rg/monthly|title=UC8Fd7MyCATxj4PvDjgHC9rg Monthly YouTube Statistics - Socialblade.com|website=socialblade.com|access-date=2019-07-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722151535/https://socialblade.com/youtube/channel/UC8Fd7MyCATxj4PvDjgHC9rg/monthly|archive-date=July 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and TR1Iceman in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tr1iceman/monthly|title=Tr1Iceman Monthly YouTube Statistics - Socialblade.com|website=socialblade.com|access-date=2019-07-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722151540/https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tr1iceman/monthly|archive-date=July 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n| gold_button          = \n| gold_year            = \n| diamond_button       = \n| diamond_year         = \n| ruby_button          = \n| ruby_year            = \n| stats_update         = {{today}}\n}}\n}}\n{{short description|American YouTuber and live streamer}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2019}}\n\n'''Desmond Daniel Amofah''' (May 12, 1990 \u2013 {{Circa|June 19, 2019}}), better known by his online alias '''Etika''', was an American [[YouTuber]], [[Online streamer|streamer]] and [[Model (person)|model]]. He was best known for his over-the-top [[Reaction video|reactions]] to [[Nintendo Direct]] presentations.\n\nFollowing several months that involved Amofah exhibiting signs of [[Mental disorder|mental illness]], as well as threatening to commit [[suicide]] on multiple occasions, he disappeared on the evening of June 19, 2019, after uploading an apologetic video in which he admitted to being mentally ill and suicidal. Amofah's body was discovered in the [[East River]] on June 25 by the [[New York City Police Department]], after it was believed he jumped from the [[Manhattan Bridge]]. On June 26, the [[Office of Chief Medical Examiner of the City of New York|Office of Chief Medical Examiner]] determined that Amofah committed [[suicide]] by drowning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/01/us/youtube-etika-desmond-amofah-suicide-trnd/index.html|title=YouTuber Etika died by suicide, medical examiner says|author=Alanne Orjoux|website=CNN|access-date=2019-08-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728085956/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/01/us/youtube-etika-desmond-amofah-suicide-trnd/index.html|archive-date=July 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDesmond Daniel Amofah was born on May 12, 1990,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Etika|title=Etika @ 999 (@Etika) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711052221/https://twitter.com/Etika|archive-date=July 11, 2019|url-status=live}}{{Self-published source|date=November 2019}}</ref> in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], to father [[Owuraku Amofah]], a Ghanaian politician and lawyer from [[Kibi, Ghana]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-news-former-dept-minister-s-son-found-dead-in-manhattan.html|title=Former Dept minister's son, Desmond Amofah, found dead in Manhattan|date=June 26, 2019|work=Graphic Online|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628085944/https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-news-former-dept-minister-s-son-found-dead-in-manhattan.html|archive-date=June 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and mother, Sabrina Amofah. Owuraku served as a member of the [[Parliament of Ghana]] for Abuakwa Central constituency from 1992 to 1996. Owuraku's father's relative (addressed by him as \"uncle\") [[Nana Akufo-Addo]], of the prominent Ghanaian [[Ofori-Atta]] family,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-371284846/why-akufo-addo-chose-caution-not-confrontation|title=\"Why Akufo-Addo Chose Caution, Not Confrontation\" by Duodu, Cameron - New African, Issue 538, April 2014 {{!}} Online Research Library: Questia|website=www.questia.com|access-date=2019-06-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627163859/https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-371284846/why-akufo-addo-chose-caution-not-confrontation|archive-date=June 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> became [[President of Ghana]] in January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Akufo-Addo-destroyed-his-family-s-good-work-Owuraku-Amofa-489084#|title=Akufo-Addo destroyed his family's good work - Owuraku Amofa|website=www.ghanaweb.com|access-date=June 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626182536/https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Akufo-Addo-destroyed-his-family-s-good-work-Owuraku-Amofa-489084|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/I-don-t-regret-supporting-Nana-Addo-Owuraku-Amofa-445958|title=I don\u2019t regret supporting Nana Addo \u2013 Owuraku Amofa|website=www.ghanaweb.com|access-date=June 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626182539/https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/I-don-t-regret-supporting-Nana-Addo-Owuraku-Amofa-445958|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Amofah had several siblings, including an older brother, Randy Amofah, who died on October 31, 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/06/etika-brother-randy-amofah-dead/|title=Etika\u2019s Older Brother Randy Amofah Died in 2010|last=Bicks|first=Emily|date=2019-06-25|work=[[Heavy.com]]|language=en|access-date=2019-06-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626185258/https://heavy.com/news/2019/06/etika-brother-randy-amofah-dead/|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> from an [[asthma attack]] while driving through a [[Dust storm|sandstorm]] in [[Ghana]], according to Amofah's ex-girlfriend Christine Cardona.\n\n==Career==\n===Modeling, streaming and YouTube career===\nPrior to the ''Etika'' branding, Amofah was active in modeling and rapping, having released an independently produced [[mixtape]] titled \"Written In Ice\" in 2007, under his pseudonym, \"Iceman\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/artists/Etika|title=Etika|website=Genius|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626181505/https://genius.com/artists/Etika|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He started modeling in 2011 and continued until 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.modelmayhem.com/2187131|title=Desmond Amofah|website=www.modelmayhem.com|access-date=2019-06-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602092230/http://www.modelmayhem.com/2187131|archive-date=June 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Amofah stated in a [[Twitter#Tweets|tweet]] that the name Etika came from the 2003 video game ''[[Sonic Battle]]'', of which he was a fan in his youth. In the game, players could input a [[cheat code]] titled \"EkiTa\" into the game. When Amofah was 12, he simply switched the T's place with the K's as he \"liked that result better.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/etika/status/508630795452682240?lang|title=Where did the name \"Etika\" come from?|date=Sep 7, 2014|website=Twitter|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016132054/https://twitter.com/etika/status/508630795452682240?lang|archive-date=October 16, 2019|url-status=live}}{{Self-published source|date=November 2019}}</ref> He started using [[YouTube]] to broadcast his gaming and reaction streams in 2012 under his original username \"EWNetwork\" (meaning \"Etika World Network\"). It was originally planned for the channel's content to be produced collaboratively by a variety of users including Amofah himself, but such plans never materialized.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48756120|website=BBC|title=Etika: Body found in search is missing YouTuber|date=June 25, 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626044929/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48756120|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Prior to the closure of his main channel on YouTube in 2018, he had more than 800,000 subscribers between his YouTube and [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] channels, and within months after creating a second YouTube channel, known as \"EtikaFRFX\", he had gained more than 130,000 subscribers.<ref name=\"kotaku\">{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/popular-youtuber-etika-dies-at-29-1835842910|title=Popular YouTuber Etika Dies At 29|last=D'Anastasio|first=Cecilia|date=June 25, 2019|work=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626001652/https://kotaku.com/popular-youtuber-etika-dies-at-29-1835842910|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/25/us/new-york-missing-youtuber-found-dead/index.html|website=CNN|title=Body pulled from the East River is that of missing YouTuber Etika, New York police say|first=Alanne|last=Orjoux|date=June 25, 2019|accessdate=June 25, 2019|publisher=[[CNN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190625214857/https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/25/us/new-york-missing-youtuber-found-dead/index.html|archive-date=June 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAmofah's content was typically described as Nintendo-focused.<ref name=\"switchfake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/11/17/13669064/nintendo-switch-fake-hoax-youtube|website=Polygon|title=Why do people keep making fake Nintendo consoles?|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=October 17, 2016|accessdate=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426212210/http://www.polygon.com/2016/11/17/13669064/nintendo-switch-fake-hoax-youtube|archive-date=April 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He frequently streamed reactions, often over-the-top, to [[Nintendo Direct]] presentations, which usually involved him screaming and falling out of his chair in elated shock.<ref name=\"polygon mental health\" /> He dubbed his fans the \"Joy-Con Boyz\", after the [[Nintendo Switch]] controller known as the [[Joy-Con]]<ref name=\"kotaku\" /> and would frequently end his videos with his signature catchphrase \"Take care of yourself. Have yourself a damn good one!\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/11/09/mural-honoring-youtuber-etika-created-by-fans-in-new-york | title = Mural Honoring YouTuber Etika Created by Fans in New York | first = Matt | last = Kim | date = November 8, 2019 | accessdate = November 8, 2019 | work = [[IGN]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191109003425/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/11/09/mural-honoring-youtuber-etika-created-by-fans-in-new-york | archive-date = November 9, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref> In November 2016, two videos of Amofah's where he purported to have a Nintendo Switch console before its 2017 release gained noterierty and were scrutinized by fans. It would eventually be learned the model Amofah was using was [[3D printing|3D-printed]] by fellow YouTuber \"Sandqvist\" at his request.<ref name=\"switchfake\" /><ref>*{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/11/weirdness_streamer_claims_to_have_nintendo_switch_flaunts_it_during_live_broadcast|title=Weirdness: Streamer Claims To Have Nintendo Switch, Flaunts It During Live Broadcast|last=Life|first=Nintendo|date=November 14, 2016|website=Nintendo Life|language=en-GB|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171224021250/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/11/weirdness_streamer_claims_to_have_nintendo_switch_flaunts_it_during_live_broadcast|archive-date=December 24, 2017|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/that-youtuber-s-infamous-nintendo-switch-is-fake-1789096291|title=That YouTuber's Infamous 'Nintendo Switch' Is Fake [CORRECTED]|last=D'Anastasio|first=Cecilia|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522092916/https://kotaku.com/that-youtuber-s-infamous-nintendo-switch-is-fake-1789096291|archive-date=May 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies and channel terminations===\nIn June 2017, Amofah revealed himself to be the victim of multiple \"fake donations\", or \"chargebacks\" of large amounts of money sent to his [[PayPal]] account via stream donations, which would jostle Amofah with hundreds of dollars in processing fees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/youtuber-reminds-fans-how-much-fake-donations-can-hurt-1796342324|title=YouTuber Reminds Fans How Much Fake Donations Can Hurt|last=D'Anastasio|first=Cecilia|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624172436/https://kotaku.com/youtuber-reminds-fans-how-much-fake-donations-can-hurt-1796342324|archive-date=June 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Amofah uploaded [[pornography]] to his YouTube channel EWNetwork (then titled Etika), which violated YouTube's policies and consequently led to the channel's termination. He later ended up getting his second channel EtikaFRFX terminated in April 2019 for the same reason.<ref name=\"Detained by police\">{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/youtuber-etika-livestreams-himself-getting-detained-by-1834393923|title=YouTuber Etika Livestreams Himself Getting Detained By Police To 19,000 Viewers|last=D'Anastasio|first=Cecilia|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626001656/https://kotaku.com/youtuber-etika-livestreams-himself-getting-detained-by-1834393923|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes\" /> He was also banned from [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] that year for using a [[Homophobia|homophobic]] slur during a stream.<ref name=\"ETASHM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-anti-semitic-homophobic-tweets/|title=Etika tweets anti-Semitic, homophobic messages\u2014then gets arrested|date=April 29, 2019|website=The Daily Dot|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514045751/https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-anti-semitic-homophobic-tweets/|archive-date=May 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the termination of his channel, Amofah posted cryptic messages to social media, including the statement \"it's my turn to die\", coupled with a screenshot of his terminated account. Several of his followers felt that the messages and posts were very suicidal in nature, which quickly created a panic within his following.<ref name=\"Detained by police\" /><ref name=\"the verge\" /> Amofah took to social media that evening to confirm his well-being, along with other streamers who professed to having seen him safe and sound in person, so as to allay his followers' fears.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/etika-responds-suicide-attempt-reddit-twitch-youtube-update-1189507|title=ETIKA RESPONDS TO SUICIDE ATTEMPT RUMORS ON REDDIT, SAYING 'YAY I BROKE THE WORLD'|first=Maria|last=Vultaggio|date=October 26, 2018|accessdate=June 25, 2019|work=[[Newsweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123031259/https://www.newsweek.com/etika-responds-suicide-attempt-reddit-twitch-youtube-update-1189507|archive-date=January 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He later apologized on his [[subreddit]] r/EtikaRedditNetwork.<ref name=\"Detained by police\" />\n\nOn April 16, 2019, Amofah tweeted that he was going to kill himself with a [[pistol]] he bought from a gun store in [[Long Island]], which led to his arrest and hospitalization. Christine Cardona, who had dated Amofah from 2011 to 2017, confirmed his well-being, and that she had been \"observing him all day\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/etika-twitter-thealicepika-youtube-what-happened-savonarola-1397917|title=What happened to Etika? Streamer handcuffed and hospitalized after suicidal Twitter outburst|first=Steven|last=Asarch|date=April 16, 2019|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623051250/https://www.newsweek.com/etika-twitter-thealicepika-youtube-what-happened-savonarola-1397917|archive-date=June 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Days later, he posted a [[Photo manipulation#Photoshopping|photoshopped]] picture of himself holding a gun which Cardona later confirmed was fake. On April 29, after tweeting a vast quantity of cryptic messages, including homophobic and ethnic slurs (that were promptly deleted),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-etika-twitter-sky-williams-health-1408575|title=Etika is back on Twitter, posting pictures with guns and anti-semitic ideology|last=EDT|first=Steven Asarch On 4/29/19 at 1:07 PM|date=2019-04-29|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618045507/https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-etika-twitter-sky-williams-health-1408575|archive-date=June 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> he blocked close friends of his, including fellow YouTuber Sky Williams.<ref name=\"ETASHM\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-etika-twitter-sky-williams-health-1408575|title=Etika is back on Twitter, posting pictures with guns and anti-semitic ideology|first=Steven|last=Asarch|date=April 29, 2019|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618045507/https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-etika-twitter-sky-williams-health-1408575|archive-date=June 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that day, he live-streamed himself getting detained by police to over 19,000 viewers on [[Instagram]] Live, after a concerned fan had notified police about his alarmingly erratic nature during the livestream.<ref name=\"Detained by police\" /><ref name=\"Purge\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-purge-all-life-keemstar-twitch/|title=Twitch star Etika says he wants to 'purge all life' in bonkers interview|date=May 1, 2019|website=The Daily Dot|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501180557/https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-purge-all-life-keemstar-twitch/|archive-date=May 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was also detained again later that same week for assaulting a police officer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-police-fight/|title=Etika reportedly detained after fighting police officer|date=May 2, 2019|website=The Daily Dot|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516000104/https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-police-fight/|archive-date=May 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Amofah would then make an appearance on the YouTube channel \"DramaAlert\", run by Internet personality [[Keemstar]], for an interview, in which he stated he was the \"[[antichrist]]\" and that he wanted to \"purge all life\".<ref name=\"Purge\" /><ref name=\"dailydot keemstar\">{{cite web | url = https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-mom-keemstar/ | title = Etika\u2019s mom defends Keemstar, says YouTuber isn\u2019t to blame for suicide | first = Josh | last = Katzowitz | date = July 1, 2019 | accessdate = July 1, 2019 | work = [[The Daily Dot]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190701172901/https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-mom-keemstar/ | archive-date = July 1, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance and death==\nIn the late evening on June 19, 2019, Amofah posted a YouTube video titled \"I'm sorry\" to his personal YouTube channel TR1Iceman,<ref name=\"the verge\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/25/18714532/desmond-afoah-etika-youtube-nypd-statement|title=Popular YouTuber Desmond 'Etika' Amofah found dead|first=Julia|last=Alexander|date=June 25, 2019|accessdate=June 25, 2019|work=[[The Verge]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626020059/https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/25/18714532/desmond-afoah-etika-youtube-nypd-statement|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> alluding to his suicidal thoughts as he was walking down New York City streets. In the video he admitted to having mental health issues, struggling with the attention he had gained from streaming, and apologized for pushing people away from him.<ref name=\"bbc\" /> Amofah left a [[suicide note]] in the description of the video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/you-tube-star-etika-missing-after-posting-worrying-video-with-potential-suicide-note-734387|title=YouTuber Etika missing after posting distressing video alluding to suicide [UPDATED]|website=Dexerto.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717154659/https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/you-tube-star-etika-missing-after-posting-worrying-video-with-potential-suicide-note-734387|archive-date=July 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> YouTube removed the video for violating its Community Guidelines, though Amofah's fans reposted the video to other outlets.<ref name=\"the verge\" />\n\nAmofah was last heard from at 11:16 PM [[Eastern Time]] (ET) that night<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rec7YWiFZ9w&lc=UgzC2Cip2H79FqtiQpJ4AaABAg|title=TR1Iceman {{!}} YouTube|last=Amofah|first=Desmond|date=June 19, 2019|website=YouTube|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 1, 2019}}{{Self-published source|date=November 2019}}</ref> and was reported missing to the New York Police Department (NYPD) by June 20.<ref name=\"nypost\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/21/youtube-star-etika-vanishes-after-posting-cryptic-suicidal-video/|title=YouTube star Etika vanishes after posting cryptic 'suicidal' video|last=Weissmann|first=Ruth|last2=Eustachewich|first2=Lia|date=June 21, 2019|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623004438/https://nypost.com/2019/06/21/youtube-star-etika-vanishes-after-posting-cryptic-suicidal-video/|archive-date=June 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> While the NYPD began its own search, fellow internet personalities and his fans tried to reach out to him to offer their help and show their appreciation of his work over the years.<ref name=\"petition\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/26/tech/etika-youtube-desmond-amofah-trnd/index.html|title=Fans petition YouTube to restore late vlogger Etika's account|first=Allen|last=Kim|date=June 26, 2019|accessdate=June 26, 2019|work=[[CNN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626155816/https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/26/tech/etika-youtube-desmond-amofah-trnd/index.html|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, the same day of Amofah's disappearance, his belongings were discovered on the pedestrian walkway of the [[Manhattan Bridge]]. They included a backpack, wallet, laptop bag, cell phone, a change of clothes and a Nintendo Switch.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48743785|title=Missing YouTuber Etika's belongings found|date=June 24, 2019|access-date=June 25, 2019|language=en-GB|newspaper=British Broadcasting Corporation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626003711/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48743785|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7chicago.com/5361292/|website=ABC7 Chicago|title=YouTube star Etika missing, fans concerned after recent video|date=June 24, 2019|publisher=[[WLS-TV]]|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626181503/https://abc7chicago.com/5361292/|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On the evening of June 24, a body was observed near Pier 16, approximately half a mile (0.8&nbsp;km) down the [[East River]] from where Amofah's belongings were recovered, and reported to the NYPD.<ref name=\"kotaku\" /> By the morning of June 25, the NYPD and emergency medical services had recovered the body, confirmed it was Amofah, and that he was dead at the point of recovery.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/etika-found-dead-missing-youtuber-desmond-amofah-new-york-tr1iceman-2019-06-25/ |title=Missing YouTuber Desmond \"Etika\" Amofah found dead in New York |first=Sophie |last=Lewis |date=25 June 2019 |access-date=26 June 2019 |work=[[CBS News]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive Inc.]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626180651/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/etika-found-dead-missing-youtuber-desmond-amofah-new-york-tr1iceman-2019-06-25/ |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The  [[Office of Chief Medical Examiner of the City of New York|Office of Chief Medical Examiner]] confirmed the cause of death was suicide by drowning the following day.<ref name=\"bbc\" /><ref name=\"abc cause\">{{cite web|last1=Jacobo|first1=Julia|title=YouTube gaming personality Desmond 'Etika' Amofah's died by suicide, officials say|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/youtube-gaming-personality-desmond-etika-amofah-found-dead/story?id=63936521|website=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=June 26, 2019|date=June 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626000911/https://abcnews.go.com/US/youtube-gaming-personality-desmond-etika-amofah-found-dead/story?id=63936521|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\nAmofah's death highlighted social media platforms' handling of posts by users who appear at risk with mental illness or who are contemplating suicide. YouTube, in removing Amofah's final video, stated that removal of such videos is standard practice to \"reduce the potential for copycat acts of self-harm, videos that express suicidal ideation\", and as part of this, sent the uploader information related to national suicide hotlines to provide help.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/26/style/etika-dead.html|title=Etika, a YouTube Personality, Is Mourned by Fans|first=Christine|last=Hauser|date=June 26, 2019|accessdate=June 26, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626203942/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/26/style/etika-dead.html|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBecause of Amofah's activities in the months prior to his disappearance, some of his followers took these previous events as a humorous performance by Amofah rather than signs of him struggling with his mental health. Following his death, mental health researchers found several videos Amofah had posted that showed evidence of his troubled state but were taken as jokes by some of his viewers, rather than actual cries for help. As a result, some took Amofah's final video as yet another joke and disregarded any concern over his well-being; [[Keemstar]] initially thought Amofah's final video was a pre-meditated [[publicity stunt]], and stated after Amofah's death that \"I was never fully convinced that he was mentally ill or in trouble because of our private convos.\"<ref name=\"polygon mental health\"/> The aforementioned mental health researchers stressed the need to make more people on social media informed about the signs of mental illness, depression, and suicidal thoughts, so that they are able to recognize when people in a mindset similar to Amofah's are in danger and need support.<ref name=\"polygon mental health\">{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2019/7/2/20677759/etika-desmond-amofah-mental-health-illness-youtube | title = Too many people took Etika\u2019s mental health struggles as a joke | first = Patrick | last = Herandez | date = July 2, 2019 | accessdate = July 3, 2019 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190702181147/https://www.polygon.com/2019/7/2/20677759/etika-desmond-amofah-mental-health-illness-youtube | archive-date = July 2, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/27/18759603/desmond-etika-amofah-death-youtube-creator-mental-health | title = YouTuber Etika\u2019s death spurs conversation about how viewers react to creators\u2019 mental health struggles | first = Julia | last = Alexander | date = June 27, 2019 | accessdate = July 3, 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190703173241/https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/27/18759603/desmond-etika-amofah-death-youtube-creator-mental-health | archive-date = July 3, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref> Keemstar briefly became a target of some of Amofah's fans, who blamed him for Amofah's suicide due to the \"DramaAlert\" interview and statements made in tweets prior to and following the interview. Amofah's mother wrote to these fans to assure them that Keemstar was in no way responsible for Amofah's death, stating that \"Etika loved Keemstar's show\" and only wanted to make a memorable appearance on it.<ref name=\"dailydot keemstar\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nFollowing Amofah's suicide, fans on Twitter and in emails asked that YouTube re-upload Amofah's final video to help memorialize him. A [[Change.org]] petition was started and initially garnered more than 380,000 signatures, but later dropped to 197,000 signatures after many fraudulent signatures from [[internet bot]]s were removed. It asked for Amofah's original channel to be restored to preserve his legacy.<ref name=\"the verge\" /><ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/etika-desmond-amofah-youtube-found-dead-1203252700/|title=Gaming YouTuber Desmond 'Etika' Amofah Found Dead, NYPD Says|first=Todd|last=Spangler|date=June 25, 2019|accessdate=June 25, 2019|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626181505/https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/etika-desmond-amofah-youtube-found-dead-1203252700/|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"petition\" /> Another Change.org petition with over a million signatures, which later dropped to more than 200,000 signatures for similar reasons, called for Amofah to be buried at YouTube headquarters, which he stated as his wish during an earlier livestream.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/25/etika-wanted-buried-front-youtube-hq-police-confirm-gamers-death-10071622/ | title = Etika wanted to be buried in front of YouTube HQ as police confirm gamer\u2019s death | first = Mel | last = Evans | date = June 25, 2019 | accessdate = June 28, 2019 | work = [[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190628223006/https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/25/etika-wanted-buried-front-youtube-hq-police-confirm-gamers-death-10071622/ | archive-date = June 28, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nFans later erected a memorial on Amofah's behalf on the pedestrian walkway of the Manhattan Bridge, leaving letters, [[fan art]], [[Twizzlers]], Nintendo-related products and other [[memorabilia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insideedition.com/fans-create-memorial-gamer-etika-new-york-54046|title=Fans Create Memorial for Gamer Etika in New York|date=2019-06-28|website=Inside Edition|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701154631/https://www.insideedition.com/fans-create-memorial-gamer-etika-new-york-54046|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2019, YouTuber Abe Hunter announced he was the owner and operator of Amofah's website<ref>{{cite tweet |user=pressabetostart|number=1143610944708386817 |date = 25 June 2019 |title=So, I was working on something for Etika a while back & because of that I still own http://etikaworldnetwork.com}}{{Self-published source|date=November 2019}}</ref> and converted it into a fundraiser site where 100% of the profits are donated to [[National Alliance on Mental Illness]] (NAMI) in Amofah's name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://etikaworldnetwork.myshopify.com/|title=Etika World Network|website=etikaworldnetwork|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710174036/https://etikaworldnetwork.myshopify.com/|archive-date=July 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 15, 2019 on behalf of the JOYCONBOYZ community; Abe Hunter donated the $11,315.25 raised to [[National Alliance on Mental Illness]] (NAMI) in memory of Amofah.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=namicommunicate |author-link=National Alliance on Mental Illness |number=1150816136751124480 |date=July 15, 2019 |title=Thank you to the #JOYCONBOYZ for their donation of $11,315.25 in memory of Desmond Amofah aka \"Etika\" from Abe of Blockhead Entertainment LLC. We appreciate your support!.}}</ref>\n\nOn July 21, 2019, YouTuber [[PewDiePie]] started a fundraiser on the [[crowdfunding]] website [[GoFundMe]] with American actor [[Jack Black]] for the [[National Alliance on Mental Illness]] (NAMI), due to the death of Amofah. PewDiePie and Black streamed themselves playing ''[[Minecraft]]'' together to raise money for their fundraiser. PewDiePie donated $10,000 to the fundraiser and raised over $30,000 for NAMI.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/07/21/pewdiepie-donates-8000-content-creators-mental-health-charity-honour-etika-10436272/|title=PewDiePie donates \u00a38000 to mental health charity in honour of Etika|date=2019-07-21|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727155812/https://metro.co.uk/2019/07/21/pewdiepie-donates-8000-content-creators-mental-health-charity-honour-etika-10436272/|archive-date=July 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn August 13, 2019, an [[Indiegogo]] campaign was started on Etika's behalf. The Charity campaign was created to earn donations for [[The Jed Foundation]]. Contributors to the campaign received a custom made pair of Etika themed joy-cons, dubbed \"Etikons\" <ref>https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/etikons-custom-etika-themed-joy-cons-for-charity--2/x/22111641#/</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 2019, it was revealed that after raising the initial $11,315.25 for [[National Alliance on Mental Illness]] (NAMI),<ref>{{cite tweet |user=namicommunicate |author-link=National Alliance on Mental Illness |number=1150816136751124480 |date=July 15, 2019 |title=Thank you to the #JOYCONBOYZ for their donation of $11,315.25 in memory of Desmond Amofah aka \"Etika\" from Abe of Blockhead Entertainment LLC. We appreciate your support!.}}{{Self-published source|date=November 2019}}</ref> YouTubers Abe Hunter and Double-A worked with Mural Artist BK FOXX, Graffiti artist Kestaadm and JMZWalls to create a 40-feet long mural dedicated to Amofah in [[Bushwick, Brooklyn]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/fans-honor-deceased-youtuber-etika-with-a-stunning-mura-1839725766 | title = Fans Honor Deceased YouTuber Etika With A Stunning Mural | first = Cecelia | last = D'Anastasio | date = November 8, 2019 | accessdate = November 8, 2019 | work = [[Kotaku]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191108215035/https://kotaku.com/fans-honor-deceased-youtuber-etika-with-a-stunning-mura-1839725766 | archive-date = November 8, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref> The mural was created to celebrate Amofah's life and to help bring awareness to mental health. The mural's location was added as a virtual \"Pok\u00e9Stop\" in the augmented reality game ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Go]]'' in February 2020 after over 350,000 people requested Nintendo to add it in memory of Amofah.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2020/2/25/21152509/pokemon-go-etika-desmond-amofah-joycon-boyz-mural-pokestop-memorial | title = Etika\u2019s face is now a Pok\u00e9mon Go stop, thanks to a YouTuber and his fans | first = Patricia | last = Hernandez | date = February 25, 2020 | accessdate = February 25, 2020 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of solved missing persons cases]]\n*[[List of YouTubers]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|8813048}}\n* {{YouTube|Etika|u=TR1Iceman}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|New York City|Internet|Video games}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:2010s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:African-American male models]]\n[[Category:American people of Ghanaian descent]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Deaths by drowning]]\n[[Category:Formerly missing people found dead]]\n[[Category:Gaming YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Internet-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Let's Players]]\n[[Category:Male models who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in New York]]\n[[Category:Models from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Suicides by drowning in the United States]]\n[[Category:Suicides by jumping in New York City]]\n[[Category:Suicides in New York City]]\n[[Category:Twitch streamers]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels launched in 2012]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels closed in 2018]]\n[[Category:YouTube controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Etika\n| image              = Etika in 2019 - 2.jpg\n| caption            = Etika in May 2019\n| birth_name         = Desmond Daniel Amofah\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1990|5|12}}\n| birth_place        = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]], U.S.\n| nationality        = [[Americans|American]]\n| height             = {{convert|6|ft|6|in|m}}<ref>{{cite web | url = https://heavy.com/entertainment/2018/10/etika/ | title = Is Etika OK? YouTuber Writes \u2018It\u2019s My Turn to Die\u2019 on Reddit | first = Paul | last=  Farrell | date = October 26, 2018 | accessdate = March 5, 2020 | work = [[Heavy (website)|Heavy]] }}</ref>\n| other_names        = {{ubl|Iceman}}\n| occupation         = {{Flatlist|\n*[[YouTuber]]\n*[[Online streamer|streamer]]\n*[[Model (person)|model]]\n}}\n| years_active       = 2011\u20132015 (model)<br/>2012\u20132019 (YouTuber)\n| death_date         = {{circa|{{Death date and age|2019|06|19|1990|5|12}}|lk=yes|i=yes}}\n| death_cause        = [[Suicide methods#Drowning|Suicide by drowning]]\n| death_place        = [[Manhattan]], New York, U.S.\n| parents            = {{plainlist|\n*[[Owuraku Amofah]] (father)\n*Sabrina Amofah (mother)\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|etikaworldnetwork.com}}\n| module             = {{Infobox YouTube personality\n| embed = yes\n| channels       = {{ubl|[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCh0SxnImUvpWs_ZfEoyhkMA EWNetwork] (terminated)|[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC8Fd7MyCATxj4PvDjgHC9rg EtikaFRFX] (terminated)|[https://www.youtube.com/user/Tr1Iceman TR1Iceman]|[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCeVmD7fCjUo5Nqk35zcF6Og E Live]}}\n| years_active         = 2012\u20132019\n| catchphrase(s)       = {{ubl|\"What's going on guys? Etika, from the Etika World Network here.\"|\"Take care of yourselves, and of course, as usual, please have yourself a damn good one.\"}}\n| genre             = {{flatlist|\n* [[Let's Play]]\n* [[Reaction_video|react]]\n* [[vlog]]\n* [[comedy]]\n}}\n| subscribers          = 1.3 million (combined)\n| subscriber_date      = \n| views                = 145 million (combined)\n| view_date            = \n| network              = \n| associated_acts      = \n| silver_button        = yes \n| silver_year          = 2015{{efn|Amofah passed 100,000 subscribers on three channels; EWNetwork in 2015, EtikaFRFX in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/channel/UC8Fd7MyCATxj4PvDjgHC9rg/monthly|title=UC8Fd7MyCATxj4PvDjgHC9rg Monthly YouTube Statistics - Socialblade.com|website=socialblade.com|access-date=2019-07-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722151535/https://socialblade.com/youtube/channel/UC8Fd7MyCATxj4PvDjgHC9rg/monthly|archive-date=July 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and TR1Iceman in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tr1iceman/monthly|title=Tr1Iceman Monthly YouTube Statistics - Socialblade.com|website=socialblade.com|access-date=2019-07-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722151540/https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/tr1iceman/monthly|archive-date=July 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n| gold_button          = \n| gold_year            = \n| diamond_button       = \n| diamond_year         = \n| ruby_button          = \n| ruby_year            = \n| stats_update         = {{today}}\n}}\n}}\n{{short description|American YouTuber and live streamer}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2019}}\n\n'''Desmond Daniel Amofah''' (May 12, 1990 \u2013 {{Circa|June 19, 2019}}), better known by his online alias '''Etika''', was an American [[YouTuber]], [[Online streamer|streamer]] and [[Model (person)|model]]. He was best known for his over-the-top [[Reaction video|reactions]] to [[Nintendo Direct]] presentations, of which many became popular [[Internet meme|internet memes.]]\n\nFollowing several months that involved Amofah exhibiting signs of [[Mental disorder|mental illness]], as well as threatening to commit [[suicide]] on multiple occasions, he disappeared on the evening of June 19, 2019, after uploading an apologetic video in which he admitted to being mentally ill and suicidal. Amofah's body was discovered in the [[East River]] on June 25 by the [[New York City Police Department]], after it was believed he jumped from the [[Manhattan Bridge]]. On June 26, the [[Office of Chief Medical Examiner of the City of New York|Office of Chief Medical Examiner]] determined that Amofah committed [[suicide]] by drowning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/01/us/youtube-etika-desmond-amofah-suicide-trnd/index.html|title=YouTuber Etika died by suicide, medical examiner says|author=Alanne Orjoux|website=CNN|access-date=2019-08-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728085956/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/01/us/youtube-etika-desmond-amofah-suicide-trnd/index.html|archive-date=July 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDesmond Daniel Amofah was born on May 12, 1990,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Etika|title=Etika @ 999 (@Etika) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711052221/https://twitter.com/Etika|archive-date=July 11, 2019|url-status=live}}{{Self-published source|date=November 2019}}</ref> in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], to father [[Owuraku Amofah]], a Ghanaian politician and lawyer from [[Kibi, Ghana]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-news-former-dept-minister-s-son-found-dead-in-manhattan.html|title=Former Dept minister's son, Desmond Amofah, found dead in Manhattan|date=June 26, 2019|work=Graphic Online|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628085944/https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-news-former-dept-minister-s-son-found-dead-in-manhattan.html|archive-date=June 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and mother, Sabrina Amofah. Owuraku served as a member of the [[Parliament of Ghana]] for Abuakwa Central constituency from 1992 to 1996. Owuraku's father's relative (addressed by him as \"uncle\") [[Nana Akufo-Addo]], of the prominent Ghanaian [[Ofori-Atta]] family,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-371284846/why-akufo-addo-chose-caution-not-confrontation|title=\"Why Akufo-Addo Chose Caution, Not Confrontation\" by Duodu, Cameron - New African, Issue 538, April 2014 {{!}} Online Research Library: Questia|website=www.questia.com|access-date=2019-06-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627163859/https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-371284846/why-akufo-addo-chose-caution-not-confrontation|archive-date=June 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> became [[President of Ghana]] in January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Akufo-Addo-destroyed-his-family-s-good-work-Owuraku-Amofa-489084#|title=Akufo-Addo destroyed his family's good work - Owuraku Amofa|website=www.ghanaweb.com|access-date=June 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626182536/https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Akufo-Addo-destroyed-his-family-s-good-work-Owuraku-Amofa-489084|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/I-don-t-regret-supporting-Nana-Addo-Owuraku-Amofa-445958|title=I don\u2019t regret supporting Nana Addo \u2013 Owuraku Amofa|website=www.ghanaweb.com|access-date=June 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626182539/https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/I-don-t-regret-supporting-Nana-Addo-Owuraku-Amofa-445958|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Amofah had several siblings, including an older brother, Randy Amofah, who died on October 31, 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/06/etika-brother-randy-amofah-dead/|title=Etika\u2019s Older Brother Randy Amofah Died in 2010|last=Bicks|first=Emily|date=2019-06-25|work=[[Heavy.com]]|language=en|access-date=2019-06-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626185258/https://heavy.com/news/2019/06/etika-brother-randy-amofah-dead/|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> from an [[asthma attack]] while driving through a [[Dust storm|sandstorm]] in [[Ghana]], according to Amofah's ex-girlfriend Christine Cardona.\n\n==Career==\n===Modeling, streaming and YouTube career===\nPrior to the ''Etika'' branding, Amofah was active in modeling and rapping, having released an independently produced [[mixtape]] titled \"Written In Ice\" in 2007, under his pseudonym, \"Iceman\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/artists/Etika|title=Etika|website=Genius|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626181505/https://genius.com/artists/Etika|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He started modeling in 2011 and continued until 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.modelmayhem.com/2187131|title=Desmond Amofah|website=www.modelmayhem.com|access-date=2019-06-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602092230/http://www.modelmayhem.com/2187131|archive-date=June 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Amofah stated in a [[Twitter#Tweets|tweet]] that the name Etika came from the 2003 video game ''[[Sonic Battle]]'', of which he was a fan in his youth. In the game, players could input a [[cheat code]] titled \"EkiTa\" into the game. When Amofah was 12, he simply switched the T's place with the K's as he \"liked that result better.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/etika/status/508630795452682240?lang|title=Where did the name \"Etika\" come from?|date=Sep 7, 2014|website=Twitter|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016132054/https://twitter.com/etika/status/508630795452682240?lang|archive-date=October 16, 2019|url-status=live}}{{Self-published source|date=November 2019}}</ref> He started using [[YouTube]] to broadcast his gaming and reaction streams in 2012 under his original username \"EWNetwork\" (meaning \"Etika World Network\"). It was originally planned for the channel's content to be produced collaboratively by a variety of users including Amofah himself, but such plans never materialized.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48756120|website=BBC|title=Etika: Body found in search is missing YouTuber|date=June 25, 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626044929/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48756120|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Prior to the closure of his main channel on YouTube in 2018, he had more than 800,000 subscribers between his YouTube and [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] channels, and within months after creating a second YouTube channel, known as \"EtikaFRFX\", he had gained more than 130,000 subscribers.<ref name=\"kotaku\">{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/popular-youtuber-etika-dies-at-29-1835842910|title=Popular YouTuber Etika Dies At 29|last=D'Anastasio|first=Cecilia|date=June 25, 2019|work=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626001652/https://kotaku.com/popular-youtuber-etika-dies-at-29-1835842910|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/25/us/new-york-missing-youtuber-found-dead/index.html|website=CNN|title=Body pulled from the East River is that of missing YouTuber Etika, New York police say|first=Alanne|last=Orjoux|date=June 25, 2019|accessdate=June 25, 2019|publisher=[[CNN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190625214857/https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/25/us/new-york-missing-youtuber-found-dead/index.html|archive-date=June 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAmofah's content was typically described as Nintendo-focused.<ref name=\"switchfake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/11/17/13669064/nintendo-switch-fake-hoax-youtube|website=Polygon|title=Why do people keep making fake Nintendo consoles?|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=October 17, 2016|accessdate=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426212210/http://www.polygon.com/2016/11/17/13669064/nintendo-switch-fake-hoax-youtube|archive-date=April 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He frequently streamed reactions, often over-the-top, to [[Nintendo Direct]] presentations, which usually involved him screaming and falling out of his chair in elated shock.<ref name=\"polygon mental health\" /> He dubbed his fans the \"Joy-Con Boyz\", after the [[Nintendo Switch]] controller known as the [[Joy-Con]]<ref name=\"kotaku\" /> and would frequently end his videos with his signature catchphrase \"Take care of yourself. Have yourself a damn good one!\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/11/09/mural-honoring-youtuber-etika-created-by-fans-in-new-york | title = Mural Honoring YouTuber Etika Created by Fans in New York | first = Matt | last = Kim | date = November 8, 2019 | accessdate = November 8, 2019 | work = [[IGN]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191109003425/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/11/09/mural-honoring-youtuber-etika-created-by-fans-in-new-york | archive-date = November 9, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref> In November 2016, two videos of Amofah's where he purported to have a Nintendo Switch console before its 2017 release gained noterierty and were scrutinized by fans. It would eventually be learned the model Amofah was using was [[3D printing|3D-printed]] by fellow YouTuber \"Sandqvist\" at his request.<ref name=\"switchfake\" /><ref>*{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/11/weirdness_streamer_claims_to_have_nintendo_switch_flaunts_it_during_live_broadcast|title=Weirdness: Streamer Claims To Have Nintendo Switch, Flaunts It During Live Broadcast|last=Life|first=Nintendo|date=November 14, 2016|website=Nintendo Life|language=en-GB|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171224021250/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/11/weirdness_streamer_claims_to_have_nintendo_switch_flaunts_it_during_live_broadcast|archive-date=December 24, 2017|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/that-youtuber-s-infamous-nintendo-switch-is-fake-1789096291|title=That YouTuber's Infamous 'Nintendo Switch' Is Fake [CORRECTED]|last=D'Anastasio|first=Cecilia|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522092916/https://kotaku.com/that-youtuber-s-infamous-nintendo-switch-is-fake-1789096291|archive-date=May 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies and channel terminations===\nIn June 2017, Amofah revealed himself to be the victim of multiple \"fake donations\", or \"chargebacks\" of large amounts of money sent to his [[PayPal]] account via stream donations, which would jostle Amofah with hundreds of dollars in processing fees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/youtuber-reminds-fans-how-much-fake-donations-can-hurt-1796342324|title=YouTuber Reminds Fans How Much Fake Donations Can Hurt|last=D'Anastasio|first=Cecilia|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624172436/https://kotaku.com/youtuber-reminds-fans-how-much-fake-donations-can-hurt-1796342324|archive-date=June 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Amofah uploaded [[pornography]] to his YouTube channel EWNetwork (then titled Etika), which violated YouTube's policies and consequently led to the channel's termination. He later ended up getting his second channel EtikaFRFX terminated in April 2019 for the same reason.<ref name=\"Detained by police\">{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/youtuber-etika-livestreams-himself-getting-detained-by-1834393923|title=YouTuber Etika Livestreams Himself Getting Detained By Police To 19,000 Viewers|last=D'Anastasio|first=Cecilia|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626001656/https://kotaku.com/youtuber-etika-livestreams-himself-getting-detained-by-1834393923|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes\" /> He was also banned from [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] that year for using a [[Homophobia|homophobic]] slur during a stream.<ref name=\"ETASHM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-anti-semitic-homophobic-tweets/|title=Etika tweets anti-Semitic, homophobic messages\u2014then gets arrested|date=April 29, 2019|website=The Daily Dot|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514045751/https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-anti-semitic-homophobic-tweets/|archive-date=May 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the termination of his channel, Amofah posted cryptic messages to social media, including the statement \"it's my turn to die\", coupled with a screenshot of his terminated account. Several of his followers felt that the messages and posts were very suicidal in nature, which quickly created a panic within his following.<ref name=\"Detained by police\" /><ref name=\"the verge\" /> Amofah took to social media that evening to confirm his well-being, along with other streamers who professed to having seen him safe and sound in person, so as to allay his followers' fears.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/etika-responds-suicide-attempt-reddit-twitch-youtube-update-1189507|title=ETIKA RESPONDS TO SUICIDE ATTEMPT RUMORS ON REDDIT, SAYING 'YAY I BROKE THE WORLD'|first=Maria|last=Vultaggio|date=October 26, 2018|accessdate=June 25, 2019|work=[[Newsweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123031259/https://www.newsweek.com/etika-responds-suicide-attempt-reddit-twitch-youtube-update-1189507|archive-date=January 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He later apologized on his [[subreddit]] r/EtikaRedditNetwork.<ref name=\"Detained by police\" />\n\nOn April 16, 2019, Amofah tweeted that he was going to kill himself with a [[pistol]] he bought from a gun store in [[Long Island]], which led to his arrest and hospitalization. Christine Cardona, who had dated Amofah from 2011 to 2017, confirmed his well-being, and that she had been \"observing him all day\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/etika-twitter-thealicepika-youtube-what-happened-savonarola-1397917|title=What happened to Etika? Streamer handcuffed and hospitalized after suicidal Twitter outburst|first=Steven|last=Asarch|date=April 16, 2019|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623051250/https://www.newsweek.com/etika-twitter-thealicepika-youtube-what-happened-savonarola-1397917|archive-date=June 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Days later, he posted a [[Photo manipulation#Photoshopping|photoshopped]] picture of himself holding a gun which Cardona later confirmed was fake. On April 29, after tweeting a vast quantity of cryptic messages, including homophobic and ethnic slurs (that were promptly deleted),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-etika-twitter-sky-williams-health-1408575|title=Etika is back on Twitter, posting pictures with guns and anti-semitic ideology|last=EDT|first=Steven Asarch On 4/29/19 at 1:07 PM|date=2019-04-29|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618045507/https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-etika-twitter-sky-williams-health-1408575|archive-date=June 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> he blocked close friends of his, including fellow YouTuber Sky Williams.<ref name=\"ETASHM\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-etika-twitter-sky-williams-health-1408575|title=Etika is back on Twitter, posting pictures with guns and anti-semitic ideology|first=Steven|last=Asarch|date=April 29, 2019|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618045507/https://www.newsweek.com/youtube-etika-twitter-sky-williams-health-1408575|archive-date=June 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that day, he live-streamed himself getting detained by police to over 19,000 viewers on [[Instagram]] Live, after a concerned fan had notified police about his alarmingly erratic nature during the livestream.<ref name=\"Detained by police\" /><ref name=\"Purge\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-purge-all-life-keemstar-twitch/|title=Twitch star Etika says he wants to 'purge all life' in bonkers interview|date=May 1, 2019|website=The Daily Dot|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501180557/https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-purge-all-life-keemstar-twitch/|archive-date=May 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was also detained again later that same week for assaulting a police officer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-police-fight/|title=Etika reportedly detained after fighting police officer|date=May 2, 2019|website=The Daily Dot|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516000104/https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-police-fight/|archive-date=May 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Amofah would then make an appearance on the YouTube channel \"DramaAlert\", run by Internet personality [[Keemstar]], for an interview, in which he stated he was the \"[[antichrist]]\" and that he wanted to \"purge all life\".<ref name=\"Purge\" /><ref name=\"dailydot keemstar\">{{cite web | url = https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-mom-keemstar/ | title = Etika\u2019s mom defends Keemstar, says YouTuber isn\u2019t to blame for suicide | first = Josh | last = Katzowitz | date = July 1, 2019 | accessdate = July 1, 2019 | work = [[The Daily Dot]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190701172901/https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/etika-mom-keemstar/ | archive-date = July 1, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance and death==\nIn the late evening on June 19, 2019, Amofah posted a YouTube video titled \"I'm sorry\" to his personal YouTube channel TR1Iceman,<ref name=\"the verge\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/25/18714532/desmond-afoah-etika-youtube-nypd-statement|title=Popular YouTuber Desmond 'Etika' Amofah found dead|first=Julia|last=Alexander|date=June 25, 2019|accessdate=June 25, 2019|work=[[The Verge]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626020059/https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/25/18714532/desmond-afoah-etika-youtube-nypd-statement|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> alluding to his suicidal thoughts as he was walking down New York City streets. In the video he admitted to having mental health issues, struggling with the attention he had gained from streaming, and apologized for pushing people away from him.<ref name=\"bbc\" /> Amofah left a [[suicide note]] in the description of the video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/you-tube-star-etika-missing-after-posting-worrying-video-with-potential-suicide-note-734387|title=YouTuber Etika missing after posting distressing video alluding to suicide [UPDATED]|website=Dexerto.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717154659/https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/you-tube-star-etika-missing-after-posting-worrying-video-with-potential-suicide-note-734387|archive-date=July 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> YouTube removed the video for violating its Community Guidelines, though Amofah's fans reposted the video to other outlets.<ref name=\"the verge\" />\n\nAmofah was last heard from at 11:16 PM [[Eastern Time]] (ET) that night<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rec7YWiFZ9w&lc=UgzC2Cip2H79FqtiQpJ4AaABAg|title=TR1Iceman {{!}} YouTube|last=Amofah|first=Desmond|date=June 19, 2019|website=YouTube|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 1, 2019}}{{Self-published source|date=November 2019}}</ref> and was reported missing to the New York Police Department (NYPD) by June 20.<ref name=\"nypost\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/21/youtube-star-etika-vanishes-after-posting-cryptic-suicidal-video/|title=YouTube star Etika vanishes after posting cryptic 'suicidal' video|last=Weissmann|first=Ruth|last2=Eustachewich|first2=Lia|date=June 21, 2019|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623004438/https://nypost.com/2019/06/21/youtube-star-etika-vanishes-after-posting-cryptic-suicidal-video/|archive-date=June 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> While the NYPD began its own search, fellow internet personalities and his fans tried to reach out to him to offer their help and show their appreciation of his work over the years.<ref name=\"petition\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/26/tech/etika-youtube-desmond-amofah-trnd/index.html|title=Fans petition YouTube to restore late vlogger Etika's account|first=Allen|last=Kim|date=June 26, 2019|accessdate=June 26, 2019|work=[[CNN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626155816/https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/26/tech/etika-youtube-desmond-amofah-trnd/index.html|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, the same day of Amofah's disappearance, his belongings were discovered on the pedestrian walkway of the [[Manhattan Bridge]]. They included a backpack, wallet, laptop bag, cell phone, a change of clothes and a Nintendo Switch.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48743785|title=Missing YouTuber Etika's belongings found|date=June 24, 2019|access-date=June 25, 2019|language=en-GB|newspaper=British Broadcasting Corporation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626003711/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48743785|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7chicago.com/5361292/|website=ABC7 Chicago|title=YouTube star Etika missing, fans concerned after recent video|date=June 24, 2019|publisher=[[WLS-TV]]|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626181503/https://abc7chicago.com/5361292/|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On the evening of June 24, a body was observed near Pier 16, approximately half a mile (0.8&nbsp;km) down the [[East River]] from where Amofah's belongings were recovered, and reported to the NYPD.<ref name=\"kotaku\" /> By the morning of June 25, the NYPD and emergency medical services had recovered the body, confirmed it was Amofah, and that he was dead at the point of recovery.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/etika-found-dead-missing-youtuber-desmond-amofah-new-york-tr1iceman-2019-06-25/ |title=Missing YouTuber Desmond \"Etika\" Amofah found dead in New York |first=Sophie |last=Lewis |date=25 June 2019 |access-date=26 June 2019 |work=[[CBS News]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive Inc.]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626180651/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/etika-found-dead-missing-youtuber-desmond-amofah-new-york-tr1iceman-2019-06-25/ |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The  [[Office of Chief Medical Examiner of the City of New York|Office of Chief Medical Examiner]] confirmed the cause of death was suicide by drowning the following day.<ref name=\"bbc\" /><ref name=\"abc cause\">{{cite web|last1=Jacobo|first1=Julia|title=YouTube gaming personality Desmond 'Etika' Amofah's died by suicide, officials say|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/youtube-gaming-personality-desmond-etika-amofah-found-dead/story?id=63936521|website=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=June 26, 2019|date=June 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626000911/https://abcnews.go.com/US/youtube-gaming-personality-desmond-etika-amofah-found-dead/story?id=63936521|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\nAmofah's death highlighted social media platforms' handling of posts by users who appear at risk with mental illness or who are contemplating suicide. YouTube, in removing Amofah's final video, stated that removal of such videos is standard practice to \"reduce the potential for copycat acts of self-harm, videos that express suicidal ideation\", and as part of this, sent the uploader information related to national suicide hotlines to provide help.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/26/style/etika-dead.html|title=Etika, a YouTube Personality, Is Mourned by Fans|first=Christine|last=Hauser|date=June 26, 2019|accessdate=June 26, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626203942/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/26/style/etika-dead.html|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBecause of Amofah's activities in the months prior to his disappearance, some of his followers took these previous events as a humorous performance by Amofah rather than signs of him struggling with his mental health. Following his death, mental health researchers found several videos Amofah had posted that showed evidence of his troubled state but were taken as jokes by some of his viewers, rather than actual cries for help. As a result, some took Amofah's final video as yet another joke and disregarded any concern over his well-being; [[Keemstar]] initially thought Amofah's final video was a pre-meditated [[publicity stunt]], and stated after Amofah's death that \"I was never fully convinced that he was mentally ill or in trouble because of our private convos.\"<ref name=\"polygon mental health\"/> The aforementioned mental health researchers stressed the need to make more people on social media informed about the signs of mental illness, depression, and suicidal thoughts, so that they are able to recognize when people in a mindset similar to Amofah's are in danger and need support.<ref name=\"polygon mental health\">{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2019/7/2/20677759/etika-desmond-amofah-mental-health-illness-youtube | title = Too many people took Etika\u2019s mental health struggles as a joke | first = Patrick | last = Herandez | date = July 2, 2019 | accessdate = July 3, 2019 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190702181147/https://www.polygon.com/2019/7/2/20677759/etika-desmond-amofah-mental-health-illness-youtube | archive-date = July 2, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/27/18759603/desmond-etika-amofah-death-youtube-creator-mental-health | title = YouTuber Etika\u2019s death spurs conversation about how viewers react to creators\u2019 mental health struggles | first = Julia | last = Alexander | date = June 27, 2019 | accessdate = July 3, 2019 | work = [[The Verge]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190703173241/https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/27/18759603/desmond-etika-amofah-death-youtube-creator-mental-health | archive-date = July 3, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref> Keemstar briefly became a target of some of Amofah's fans, who blamed him for Amofah's suicide due to the \"DramaAlert\" interview and statements made in tweets prior to and following the interview. Amofah's mother wrote to these fans to assure them that Keemstar was in no way responsible for Amofah's death, stating that \"Etika loved Keemstar's show\" and only wanted to make a memorable appearance on it.<ref name=\"dailydot keemstar\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nFollowing Amofah's suicide, fans on Twitter and in emails asked that YouTube re-upload Amofah's final video to help memorialize him. A [[Change.org]] petition was started and initially garnered more than 380,000 signatures, but later dropped to 197,000 signatures after many fraudulent signatures from [[internet bot]]s were removed. It asked for Amofah's original channel to be restored to preserve his legacy.<ref name=\"the verge\" /><ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/etika-desmond-amofah-youtube-found-dead-1203252700/|title=Gaming YouTuber Desmond 'Etika' Amofah Found Dead, NYPD Says|first=Todd|last=Spangler|date=June 25, 2019|accessdate=June 25, 2019|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626181505/https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/etika-desmond-amofah-youtube-found-dead-1203252700/|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"petition\" /> Another Change.org petition with over a million signatures, which later dropped to more than 200,000 signatures for similar reasons, called for Amofah to be buried at YouTube headquarters, which he stated as his wish during an earlier livestream.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/25/etika-wanted-buried-front-youtube-hq-police-confirm-gamers-death-10071622/ | title = Etika wanted to be buried in front of YouTube HQ as police confirm gamer\u2019s death | first = Mel | last = Evans | date = June 25, 2019 | accessdate = June 28, 2019 | work = [[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190628223006/https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/25/etika-wanted-buried-front-youtube-hq-police-confirm-gamers-death-10071622/ | archive-date = June 28, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nFans later erected a memorial on Amofah's behalf on the pedestrian walkway of the Manhattan Bridge, leaving letters, [[fan art]], [[Twizzlers]], Nintendo-related products and other [[memorabilia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insideedition.com/fans-create-memorial-gamer-etika-new-york-54046|title=Fans Create Memorial for Gamer Etika in New York|date=2019-06-28|website=Inside Edition|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701154631/https://www.insideedition.com/fans-create-memorial-gamer-etika-new-york-54046|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2019, YouTuber Abe Hunter announced he was the owner and operator of Amofah's website<ref>{{cite tweet |user=pressabetostart|number=1143610944708386817 |date = 25 June 2019 |title=So, I was working on something for Etika a while back & because of that I still own http://etikaworldnetwork.com}}{{Self-published source|date=November 2019}}</ref> and converted it into a fundraiser site where 100% of the profits are donated to [[National Alliance on Mental Illness]] (NAMI) in Amofah's name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://etikaworldnetwork.myshopify.com/|title=Etika World Network|website=etikaworldnetwork|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710174036/https://etikaworldnetwork.myshopify.com/|archive-date=July 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 15, 2019 on behalf of the JOYCONBOYZ community; Abe Hunter donated the $11,315.25 raised to [[National Alliance on Mental Illness]] (NAMI) in memory of Amofah.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=namicommunicate |author-link=National Alliance on Mental Illness |number=1150816136751124480 |date=July 15, 2019 |title=Thank you to the #JOYCONBOYZ for their donation of $11,315.25 in memory of Desmond Amofah aka \"Etika\" from Abe of Blockhead Entertainment LLC. We appreciate your support!.}}</ref>\n\nOn July 21, 2019, YouTuber [[PewDiePie]] started a fundraiser on the [[crowdfunding]] website [[GoFundMe]] with American actor [[Jack Black]] for the [[National Alliance on Mental Illness]] (NAMI), due to the death of Amofah. PewDiePie and Black streamed themselves playing ''[[Minecraft]]'' together to raise money for their fundraiser. PewDiePie donated $10,000 to the fundraiser and raised over $30,000 for NAMI.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/07/21/pewdiepie-donates-8000-content-creators-mental-health-charity-honour-etika-10436272/|title=PewDiePie donates \u00a38000 to mental health charity in honour of Etika|date=2019-07-21|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727155812/https://metro.co.uk/2019/07/21/pewdiepie-donates-8000-content-creators-mental-health-charity-honour-etika-10436272/|archive-date=July 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn August 13, 2019, an [[Indiegogo]] campaign was started on Etika's behalf. The Charity campaign was created to earn donations for [[The Jed Foundation]]. Contributors to the campaign received a custom made pair of Etika themed joy-cons, dubbed \"Etikons\" <ref>https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/etikons-custom-etika-themed-joy-cons-for-charity--2/x/22111641#/</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 2019, it was revealed that after raising the initial $11,315.25 for [[National Alliance on Mental Illness]] (NAMI),<ref>{{cite tweet |user=namicommunicate |author-link=National Alliance on Mental Illness |number=1150816136751124480 |date=July 15, 2019 |title=Thank you to the #JOYCONBOYZ for their donation of $11,315.25 in memory of Desmond Amofah aka \"Etika\" from Abe of Blockhead Entertainment LLC. We appreciate your support!.}}{{Self-published source|date=November 2019}}</ref> YouTubers Abe Hunter and Double-A worked with Mural Artist BK FOXX, Graffiti artist Kestaadm and JMZWalls to create a 40-feet long mural dedicated to Amofah in [[Bushwick, Brooklyn]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/fans-honor-deceased-youtuber-etika-with-a-stunning-mura-1839725766 | title = Fans Honor Deceased YouTuber Etika With A Stunning Mural | first = Cecelia | last = D'Anastasio | date = November 8, 2019 | accessdate = November 8, 2019 | work = [[Kotaku]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191108215035/https://kotaku.com/fans-honor-deceased-youtuber-etika-with-a-stunning-mura-1839725766 | archive-date = November 8, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref> The mural was created to celebrate Amofah's life and to help bring awareness to mental health. The mural's location was added as a virtual \"Pok\u00e9Stop\" in the augmented reality game ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Go]]'' in February 2020 after over 350,000 people requested Nintendo to add it in memory of Amofah.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2020/2/25/21152509/pokemon-go-etika-desmond-amofah-joycon-boyz-mural-pokestop-memorial | title = Etika\u2019s face is now a Pok\u00e9mon Go stop, thanks to a YouTuber and his fans | first = Patricia | last = Hernandez | date = February 25, 2020 | accessdate = February 25, 2020 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of solved missing persons cases]]\n*[[List of YouTubers]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|8813048}}\n* {{YouTube|Etika|u=TR1Iceman}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|New York City|Internet|Video games}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:2010s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:African-American male models]]\n[[Category:American people of Ghanaian descent]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Deaths by drowning]]\n[[Category:Formerly missing people found dead]]\n[[Category:Gaming YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Internet-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Let's Players]]\n[[Category:Male models who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in New York]]\n[[Category:Models from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Suicides by drowning in the United States]]\n[[Category:Suicides by jumping in New York City]]\n[[Category:Suicides in New York City]]\n[[Category:Twitch streamers]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels launched in 2012]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels closed in 2018]]\n[[Category:YouTube controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Acekard", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Etika"}
{"title_page": "Hern\u00e1n Crespo", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Hern\u00e1n Crespo\n| image              = Chelsea Legends 1 Inter Forever 4 (27457022797).jpg\n| image_size         = 200\n| caption            = Crespo in 2018\n| fullname           = Hern\u00e1n Jorge Crespo\n| height             = {{convert|1.84|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"ESPN\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/_/id/11018/hern%C3%A1n-crespo?cc=5739|title=Player Profile: Hern\u00e1n Crespo|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1975|7|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Florida, Buenos Aires|Florida Este]], Argentina\n| currentclub        = [[Defensa y Justicia]] (manager)\n| position           = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| years1             = 1993\u20131996 |clubs1  = [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]              |caps1  = 62  |goals1  = 24\n| years2             = 1996\u20132000 |clubs2  = [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]                            |caps2  = 116 |goals2  = 62\n| years3             = 2000\u20132002 |clubs3  = [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]                                   |caps3  = 54  |goals3  = 39\n| years4             = 2002\u20132003 |clubs4  = [[Inter Milan]]                                        |caps4  = 18  |goals4  = 7\n| years5             = 2003\u20132008 |clubs5  = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]                               |caps5  = 49  |goals5  = 20\n| years6             = 2004\u20132005 |clubs6  = \u2192 [[A.C. Milan]] (loan)                                |caps6  = 28  |goals6  = 11\n| years7             = 2006\u20132008 |clubs7  = \u2192 [[Inter Milan]] (loan)                               |caps7  = 49  |goals7  = 18\n| years8             = 2008\u20132009 |clubs8  = [[Inter Milan]]                                        |caps8  = 14  |goals8  = 2\n| years9             = 2009\u20132010 |clubs9  = [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]]                                 |caps9  = 16  |goals9  = 5\n| years10            = 2010\u20132012 |clubs10 = [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]                            |caps10 = 46  |goals10 = 10\n| totalcaps          = 453       | totalgoals = 198\n| nationalyears1 = 1996      |nationalteam1 = [[Argentina national under-23 football team|Argentina U23]] |nationalcaps1 = 6  |nationalgoals1 = 6\n| nationalyears2 = 1995\u20132007 |nationalteam2 = [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]              |nationalcaps2 = 64 |nationalgoals2 = 35\n| manageryears1      = 2014\u20132015 | managerclubs1 = [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] (youth)\n| manageryears2      = 2015\u20132016 | managerclubs2 = [[Modena F.C. 2018|Modena]]\n| manageryears3      = 2018\u20132019 | managerclubs3 = [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Banfield|Banfield]]\n| manageryears4      = 2020\u2013     | managerclubs4 = [[Defensa y Justicia]]\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{fb|ARG}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|Football]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Atlanta]]|[[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1995 Pan American Games|1995 Mar del Plata]]|[[Football at the 1995 Pan American Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2007 Venezuela]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Hern\u00e1n Jorge Crespo''' ({{IPA-es|e\u027e\u02c8na\u014b \u02c8xo\u027exe \u02c8k\u027eespo}}; born 5 July 1975) is an Argentine professional [[Association football|football]] coach and former player. He is the current manager of [[Defensa y Justicia]].\n\nA prolific [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]], Crespo has scored over 300 goals in a career spanning 19 years. At international level, he scored 35 goals and is [[Argentina national football team#Top goalscorers|Argentina's fourth highest goalscorer]] behind only [[Sergio Ag\u00fcero]], [[Gabriel Batistuta]] and [[Lionel Messi]]. He played in three [[FIFA World Cup]]s: [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]], [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]], [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006]]. At club level, Crespo was the [[List of most expensive association football transfers|world's most expensive player]], when he was bought by [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] from [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] in 2000 for \u20ac56 million (\u00a335.5 million).<ref name=\"Record\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23903470 \"The history of the world transfer record\"]. BBC News. Retrieved 10 May 2014</ref> He was top scorer in the [[2000\u201301 Serie A]] with 26 goals, playing for Lazio.\n\nCrespo's awards include three Serie A ''[[Scudetto|scudetti]]'', a [[Copa Libertadores]], a [[Premier League]] title and an [[Olympic Games]] silver medal. In 2004, he was named by [[Pel\u00e9]] in the [[FIFA 100]] list of the world's greatest living players.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/3533891.stm |title=Pele's list of the greatest |work=BBC Sport |date=4 March 2004 |accessdate=10 May 2014 }}</ref> Crespo never received a red card during his career.<ref name=\"ESPN\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n===River Plate===\nCrespo made his debut with [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]] during the 1993\u201394 season, scoring 13 goals in 25 league appearances as River Plate won the [[Apertura and Clausura|Apertura]] league title. In 1996, he helped River win the [[Copa Libertadores]], scoring twice in the home leg of the final in [[Buenos Aires]].\n\n===Parma===\nCrespo left River Plate for [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] on 14 August 1996 after he won the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|silver medal]] with Argentina at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] and finished as the top scorer with six goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsbook24.net/?action=read&idnotizia=41328 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204060812/http://www.sportsbook24.net/?action=read&idnotizia=41328 |archivedate=4 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He failed to score in his first six months at the club and was routinely booed, with head coach [[Carlo Ancelotti]] coming in for much criticism for keeping faith with the selection of Crespo. His faith, however, vindicated \u2013 Crespo went on to score 12 times in 27 matches in [[1996\u201397 Serie A|his first Serie A season]] and Parma finished runners-up to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]. The turning point was the standing applause he received for his brace against [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] in March 1997.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.football-italia.net/node/15332|work=[[Football Italia]]|date=3 February 2012|title=Arrivederci Crespo|first=Antonio|last=Labbate|accessdate=4 February 2012}}</ref> Parma won the [[1998\u201399 Coppa Italia]] and he scored the opening goal in Parma's 3\u20130 [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] [[1999 UEFA Cup Final|final]] victory over [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]]. He had scored 80 goals in four seasons. He never scored against Franco Baresi.\n\n===Lazio===\nIn 2000, [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] broke the [[List of most expensive association football transfers|then-world transfer record]] by paying \u00a335&nbsp;million (they paid \u00a316&nbsp;million in cash and transferred [[Mat\u00edas Almeyda]] and [[S\u00e9rgio Concei\u00e7\u00e3o]]) to acquire Crespo,<ref>{{cite news |title=Lazio's \u00a340m Crespo deal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/829225.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=11 July 2000 |accessdate=1 March 2009 }}</ref> who in turn finished as Serie A's top scorer with 26 goals. Lazio, however, failed to defend its league title in 2001, and the following season, Crespo suffered from some injuries, while new signings [[Jaap Stam]] and [[Gaizka Mendieta]] failed to live up their reputations, following the departures of playmakers [[Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n]] and [[Pavel Nedv\u011bd]]. Crespo was left without the attacking support he had enjoyed in 2001, but still scored a respectable haul of goals. Lazio's financial problems, however, forced the club to sell several players, and following [[Alessandro Nesta]]'s transfer to [[A.C. Milan]], speculation over Crespo's future intensified.\n\n===Inter Milan===\nOn 31 August 2002, Crespo, expected to shine again after suffering from injuries, signed with [[Inter Milan]] as a replacement for the departed [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Crespo steps in for Ronaldo |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=32107.html |work=UEFA |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=31 August 2002 |accessdate=29 April 2014 }}</ref> for a \u20ac26&nbsp;million fee and [[Bernardo Corradi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/09/01/1030508162562.html|title=Ronaldo leaves home under police escort|accessdate=29 April 2014|work=Agencies|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> Lazio later re-valued Corradi to \u20ac5.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://media.sslazio.it/200405/255.pdf?ver=1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040721183334/http://media.sslazio.it/200405/255.pdf?ver=1 |title=PROGETTO DI BILANCIO AL 30 GIUGNO 2003 (part 1) |accessdate=26 February 2010 |archivedate=21 July 2004 |work=SS Lazio |language=Italian |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Inter was short of strikers after the highly rated [[Mohamed Kallon]] was injured in August,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.inter.it/aas/news/reader?L=en&N=4364|title= Second degree tendon injury for kallon |date=19 August 2002|accessdate=10 August 2009|publisher=Internazionale}}</ref> and only [[\u00c1lvaro Recoba]] and [[Christian Vieri]], together with reserves Bernardo Corradi and [[Nicola Ventola]], were available.\n\nCrespo scored seven goals in three appearances, along with nine goals in 12 [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] matches, until he was sidelined for four months by injury in early 2003.\n\n===Chelsea===\nCrespo was transferred to [[Premier League]] club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 26 August 2003 for a fee of reported \u00a316.8&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea sign Crespo |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/3183431.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=26 August 2003 |access-date=15 May 2011 }}</ref> which also created a controversy in alleged false accounting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Inter/Primo_Piano/2007/01_Gennaio/26/contratti.shtml|title=Crespo-Morfeo, indagine sui contratti|date=26 January 2007|access-date=18 September 2012|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Inter bought Crespo for \u20ac38 million accounting value; however, the club split the amount in February 2003 into reported \u20ac4.45 million (which would amortize normally according to the length of player contract: i.e. proportionality, zero which his contract expires), and \u20ac33.55 million in [[Italian Law 91/1981, Article 18B|special amortization fund in 10-year equal installment]] (which, although most of the players would leave the club within 10 years, the fund still appeared as an asset in balance sheet). Inter sold Crespo for an undisclosed fee, which created a huge profit if considering Crespo's value of below \u20ac4.45 million (the value weathered after his contract had excised for one year), but if considering Crespo left the club but still \"worth\" \u20ac30.195 million residual asset \"value\" in the special fund, the deal would create a huge loss. The auditor also wrote in a 2003\u201304 financial report that if the departure of Crespo combined with removing the value in the special fund would create a loss of ca. \u20ac18.8 million  (\"''qualora detta plusvalenza fosse state imputata a riduzione della voce \"Oneri pluriennali da svalutazione diritti: sarebbe scaturita una maggior perdita di ca. \u20ac18.8 millioni''\")|group=\"note\"|name=falseaccounting}} Following the transfer, Christian Vieri, Crespo's former strike partner at Inter, claimed that the club are essentially \"weakening\" by selling players of such caliber.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/aug/23/newsstory.sport|title=Vieri in a fury as Chelsea move in on \u00a322m Crespo|first=Matt|last=Scott|date=22 August 2003|publisher=|accessdate=23 July 2016}}</ref> He made his league debut on 30 August 2003 as a substitute for [[Adrian Mutu]] in a 2\u20132 home draw against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Cole checks Chelsea charge |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/3172813.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=30 August 2003 |accessdate=15 May 2011 }}</ref> On 16 September 2003, Crespo made his European debut, replacing [[Jimmy Floyd Hasselbaink]] in the [[2003\u201304 UEFA Champions League group stage|2003\u201304 Champions League group stage]], which ended in a 1\u20130 away win after a late goal from [[William Gallas]] against [[AC Sparta Prague|Sparta Prague]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea leave it late |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/champions_league/3110452.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=16 September 2003 |accessdate=15 May 2011 }}</ref> Four days later, he scored his first goals, a double, in a 5\u20130 away victory against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea crush Wolves |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/3084346.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=20 September 2003 |accessdate=15 May 2011 }}</ref> Crespo made 31 appearances (including 19 in the league) in all competitions, scoring 12 goals.\n\n===A.C. Milan (loan)===\nAfter [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]] took over as Chelsea manager for the 2004\u201305 season, Crespo became surplus to Chelsea's plans following the arrival of [[Didier Drogba]] and was loaned to A.C. Milan, as requested by then-manager [[Carlo Ancelotti]]. He scored a total of ten league goals, and scored twice in the [[2005 UEFA Champions League Final]] in a defeat to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite news |title=AC Milan 3\u20133 Liverpool (aet) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4573159.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=25 May 2005 |accessdate=15 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn scoring a Champions League goal with Milan, Crespo became the first player to score with five teams in the competition, doing so with each of the sides he had played for since moving from South America to Europe in 1996.<ref name=\"eurofutbal\">{{cite web|url=http://euro.futbal.org/EC1.scorers.php?year=0&firstYear=40&player=Hernan%20Crespo|title=Top scorers \u2013 European Champions League 1976\u20132016|publisher=|accessdate=23 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Chelsea===\nAfter Chelsea's failed attempts to land a big-name striker during the summer of 2005, Mourinho needed competition for striker Didier Drogba and decided to recall Crespo from A.C. Milan, convincing him that he had a future in England. Crespo made his first return appearance in a 2\u20131 [[2005 FA Community Shield|FA Community Shield]] win over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelsea 2\u20131 Arsenal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/4747797.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=7 August 2005 |accessdate=16 May 2011 }}</ref> He scored his first league goal of 2005 against newly promoted [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in the 93rd minute of Chelsea's season opener in a 1\u20130 win, with a left foot curler into the top corner from 25 yards.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wigan 0\u20131 Chelsea |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/4127068.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=14 August 2005 |accessdate=16 May 2011 }}</ref> The [[2005\u201306 FA Premier League|2005\u201306 league title]] was Crespo's first league title victory in European football.\n\n===Return to Inter Milan===\n====Second spell; loan from 2006 to 2008====\n[[Image:CrespoInter.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Crespo with Inter in 2007.]]\nThough he scored 13 goals in all competitions and won the 2005\u201306 Premier League, Crespo requested a return to Italy in order to rejoin A.C. Milan, but Chelsea refused and announced that Crespo would remain a Chelsea player until the club accepted a suitable offer for him. On 7 August 2006, Crespo joined Inter on a two-year loan. He scored his 125th Serie A goal against [[S.S. Robur Siena|Siena]] on 2 December 2006, and his 200th career goal in Europe on 2 April 2007. On 13 May, Crespo scored a hat-trick to help Inter defeat Lazio 4\u20133 and win the ''[[Scudetto]].''\n\n====Third spell; permanent deal====\nCrespo was released from Chelsea on 3 July 2008, following the expiration of his contract,<ref name=\"chelseafc\">[https://archive.is/20140429162652/http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/1338176 Crespo No Longer a Blue \u2013 chelseafc.com]</ref><ref name=\"FI\">{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/jul3n.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007105655/http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/jul3n.html|archivedate=7 October 2008|title=Chelsea let Crespo leave|publisher=Channel 4|date=3 July 2008|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> and was signed by Inter on a one-year contract for free. In the [[2008\u201309 Inter Milan season|2008\u201309 season]], under Jos\u00e9 Mourinho, his former manager in Chelsea, Crespo only made 13 [[2008\u201309 Serie A|Serie A]] appearances, including two starts. He was excluded from the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] squad.\n\n===Genoa===\nFollowing the expiration of his contract at Inter, Crespo was quickly snapped up by [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]], taking [[Diego Milito]]'s place, who moved in the opposite direction. On 8 June 2009, it was reported that Crespo had a medical check to formalize his transfer. Crespo cited his ambition to make the Argentina 2010 World Cup squad as one of his key reasons for making the move to Genoa.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/crespo-genoa-move-will-get-me-world-cup-248741 |title=Crespo: Genoa move will get me to World Cup |date=3 December 2009|accessdate=1 May 2014|publisher=tribalfootball.com}}</ref> On 13 September, Crespo scored his first goal of the 2009 season against [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.genoacfc.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7340&Itemid=31|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812040848/http://www.genoacfc.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7340&Itemid=31|archivedate=12 August 2012 |title=CRESPO: \"PROFESSIONALITA' E VOGLIA\" |date=8 June 2009|accessdate=9 June 2009|publisher=genoacfc.it|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Parma and retirement===\nIn January 2010, Crespo returned to Parma after the club agreed the deal with [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]] and Genoa. Crespo replaced [[Nicola Amoruso]] who left for Atalanta, while Atalanta's [[Robert Acquafresca]] moved to Genoa to replace Crespo. The Argentine striker returned after ten years to Parma. Crespo scored just once before the season's end, against [[A.S. Livorno Calcio|Livorno]]. The striker enjoyed a more successful [[2010\u201311 Serie A|2010\u201311 season]], scoring 11 goals. In doing so, he became Parma's top scorer for a fourth time, which remains a post-war club record. Despite mounting speculation of his departure, Crespo signed a one-year contract extension on 30 June 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fcparma.com/stagione/archivio-primo-piano/8985-ufficiale-crespo-un-altro-anno-a-parma.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704090813/http://www.fcparma.com/stagione/archivio-primo-piano/8985-ufficiale-crespo-un-altro-anno-a-parma.html|archivedate=4 July 2011 |title=UFFICIALE: CRESPO, UN ALTRO ANNO A PARMA|date=30 June 2011|accessdate=15 July 2011|work=Parma FC|language=Italian}}</ref> However, a lack of first-team opportunities saw Crespo and Parma mutually agree to terminate his contract on 2 February 2012, although he did vow to return to the city he had fallen in love with.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.football-italia.net/node/15304|publisher=football-italia.net|work=[[Football Italia]]|date=2 February 2012|title=Tearful Crespo quits Parma}}</ref> He is the club's all-time record goalscorer with 94 goals in 201 appearances.\n\nAlthough Crespo was signed to play in [[Bengal Premier League Soccer]] in late January 2012, with a salary of \u00a3533,000 for the two-month tournament, the competition never got underway.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/9051204/Hernan-Crespo-most-expensive-player-in-Indian-football-auction.html | title=Hernan Crespo most expensive player in Indian football auction | date=31 January 2012 | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> He clarified that his career as a footballer had finished in November 2012.<ref name=\"november 2012\">{{cite news | url=https://int.soccerway.com/news/2012/November/13/coaching-career-beckons-for-crespo/ | title=Coaching career beckons for Crespo | date=12 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Hern\u00e1n Crespo - 07FEB2007 - Francia - presidencia-govar.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Crespo with [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in 2007]]\nCrespo won his first cap for [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in a friendly match against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] in February 1995. He was a member of the Argentina side that finished runners-up in the [[1995 King Fahd Cup]], the predecessor to the [[FIFA Confederations Cup]].\n\nIn 1996, Crespo was a member of the [[Argentina national under-23 football team|Argentina men's football squad]] for the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Olympic Games]]. Crespo helped take Argentina to the final with braces against [[Spain national under-23 football team|Spain]] in the quarter-final and [[Portugal Olympic football team|Portugal]] in the semi-final. However, Argentina lost the final to [[Nigeria national under-23 football team|Nigeria]], despite Crespo scoring his sixth goal of the tournament [[Penalty kick (association football)|from the penalty spot]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=162680/index.html|title=Hernan Crespo|publisher=FIFA}}</ref>\n\nCrespo scored his first goal for the Argentina senior team in a [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|1998 World Cup qualifier]] against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] and hit a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] against [[Serbia and Montenegro national football team|FR Yugoslavia]] in a pre-World Cup friendly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mundoalbiceleste.com/Article.aspx?id=2663|title=Looking back: Argentina 3\u20131 Yugoslavia|date=3 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511131212/http://www.mundoalbiceleste.com/Article.aspx?id=2663|archivedate=11 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Crespo was called up to the [[1998 FIFA World Cup squads#Argentina|final roster]] for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]] but only made one substitute appearance, as [[Gabriel Batistuta]] led the Argentine attack. Crespo missed his kick in the [[1998 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Argentina vs England|second round]] [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] with [[England national football team|England]], but Argentina progressed 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sport/football/123666.stm|title=England pay penalty again|date=30 June 1998|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|qualification]] for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], Crespo was top scorer for Argentina with nine goals as they topped the [[CONMEBOL|South American]] group.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+World+Cup+2002%3A+IT'S+GO+FOR+BATISTUTA.-a086586599 |title=Football: World Cup 2002: IT'S GO FOR BATISTUTA|accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref> During the finals, Batistuta was again preferred to Crespo as Argentina's starting centre forward. Crespo appeared as a substitute in all three [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group F|group matches]], including the [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group F#Sweden vs Argentina|final match]] against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]], which Argentina needed to win in order to qualify for the second round. Though Crespo scored an 88th-minute equaliser, it was not to be enough and Argentina were eliminated.\n\nAfter the 2002 World Cup, Batistuta retired from international football,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/matches_wallchart/sweden_v_argentina/newsid_2038000/2038719.stm |title=Batistuta's 'sad' retirement |date=11 June 2002 |publisher=BBC}}</ref> and Crespo took over as Argentina's number 9. During the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|qualifying stage]], Crespo scored seven times, including two goals in Argentina's 3\u20131 World Cup qualifying win over [[Argentina\u2013Brazil football rivalry|arch-rivals]] [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in Buenos Aires, which made him Argentina's career scoring leader in World Cup qualifiers.\n\nCrespo scored Argentina's first goal of the 2006 World Cup in [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group C#Argentina vs C\u00f4te d'Ivoire|their opening match]] against the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]]. He also scored in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group C#Argentina vs Serbia and Montenegro|second group game]] against Serbia and Montenegro and the [[2006 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Argentina vs Mexico|second round match]] against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]]. However, Argentina's run was ended as they were knocked out by host nation [[Germany national football team|Germany]] on penalties in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Germany vs Argentina|quarter-final]].\n\nCrespo's final appearances for Argentina came at [[2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica]]. He scored twice in Argentina's 4\u20131 victory over the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] in their [[2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica#Group C|Group C]] opener, tying [[Diego Maradona]]'s team scoring record.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.inter.it/aas/news/reader?N=26786&L=en&IDINI=26788 |title=Crespo matches Maradona tally |publisher=Inter.it |date=29 June 2007 |accessdate=3 July 2007}}</ref> He then overtook Maradona in Argentina's second match, scoring a penalty kick against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]]. However, he substituted immediately after converting the kick due to injury and missed the remainder of the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/6263888.stm |title=Argentina into last eight of Copa |date=3 July 2007 |publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Copa Am\u00e9rica, Crespo did not receive any further call-ups to the national team and ended his international career with 35 goals in 64 matches, making him [[Argentina national football team#Top goalscorers|Argentina's third highest goalscorer]] of all-time, behind Gabriel Batistuta and [[Lionel Messi]].\n\n==Style of play==\nCrespo was a fast, tenacious, powerful, and complete striker, who possessed good technique, composure in possession, and an eye for goal; he also excelled in the air. A prolific and opportunistic goal-scorer, he was capable of finishing well both with his feet and with his head, and was known for his ability to score acrobatic goals.<ref name=valdanito>{{cite web|url=http://www.solocalcio.com/ritratti/crespo.htm|title=Hernan Crespo \u2013 Si avvicina il \"valdanito\"|trans-title=Hernan Crespo \u2013 The \"Valdanito\" draws nearer|publisher=Solo Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnamilan.com/nemici-storici/hernan-crespo.html|publisher=DNA Milan|title=Nemici Storici: Hernan Crespo|trans-title=Historic Enemies: Hernan Crespo|language=Italian|author1=Enrico Bonifazi|date=16 June 2013|accessdate=20 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505233529/http://dnamilan.com/nemici-storici/hernan-crespo.html|archivedate=5 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"treccani\">{{cite web|url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/hernan-jorge-crespo_(Enciclopedia-dello-Sport)/|title=CRESPO, Hernan Jorge|publisher=Treccani: Enciclopedia dello Sport (2002)|language=Italian|author1=Fabrizio Maffei|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"2002WCProfile\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/team_pages/argentina/squad/newsid_1786000/1786804.stm|title=Hernan Crespo|work=BBC Sport|date=9 April 2002|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> He was also effective off the ball due to his work-rate, tactical intelligence, and attacking movement, which he often used to provide depth for his team or create space for his teammates;<ref name=\"Cercasi anima gemella per Sheva\">{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2004/settembre/28/Cercasi_anima_gemella_per_Sheva_ga_10_0409287232.shtml|title=Cercasi anima gemella per Sheva|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|trans-title=Looking for a soulmate for Sheva|language=Italian|author1=Andrea Schianchi|date=28 September 2004|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref> he was also capable of linking up well with other forwards.<ref name=\"2002WCProfile\"/> Due to his goalscoring ability and wide range of skills, he is regarded as one of the best strikers of his generation, and as one of Serie A's best ever foreign players.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/node/15332|title=Arrivederci Crespo|publisher=Football Italia|author1=Antonio Labbate|date=3 February 2012|accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref> Despite his ability, he faced several injuries throughout his career, which limited his playing time at times.<ref name=\"treccani\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parmatoday.it/sport/crespo-lascia-parma.html|title=Crespo lascia Parma: giocher\u00e0 in India Crespo saluta Parma: se ne va l'ultima bandiera gialloblu|publisher=Parma Today|language=Italian|author1=Guglielmo Trupo|date=2 February 2011|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Nicknames===\nWhile commonly known as Hern\u00e1n, Crespo was christened Hernando Jorge Crespo, after his grandfather of the same name.{{Citation needed|date = May 2018}} His most common nickname is \"''Valdanito''\", after legendary compatriot striker [[Jorge Valdano]], as he was thought to be his heir due to their similar appearance and eye for goal. He is also called, although less often, \"''El Polaco''\" (or \"The Pole\") because his grandmother was Polish.<ref name=valdanito/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://article.abc-directory.com/article/6521|title=Short Biography of Famous Soccer Player \u2013 Hernan Crespo \u2013 Article by John Castrow \u2013 at Recreation & Sports, Soccer|publisher=|accessdate=23 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nCrespo was sponsored by sportswear company [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] and appeared in Nike commercials. In a global Nike advertising campaign in the run-up to the 2002 World Cup in Korea and Japan, Crespo starred in a \"[[Secret Tournament]]\" commercial (branded \"Scorpion KO\") directed by [[Terry Gilliam]], appearing alongside footballers such as [[Thierry Henry]], [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]], [[Francesco Totti]], [[Ronaldinho]], [[Lu\u00eds Figo]], [[Roberto Carlos]] and [[Hidetoshi Nakata]], with former player [[Eric Cantona]] as the tournament \"referee\".<ref>{{cite news |title=A lighter shoe, cooler kits, a faster ball, a Secret Tournament \u2013 every touch counts |url=http://www.nikebiz.com/story/stry_scorpion.shtml |work=NikeBiz |publisher=Nike |accessdate=21 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020602055510/http://www.nikebiz.com/story/stry_scorpion.shtml |archivedate=2 June 2002 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Claire |last=Cozens |title=Cantona hosts World Cup with a difference |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/apr/03/advertising.worldcupfootball2002?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487 |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media |date=3 April 2002 |accessdate=21 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Post-playing and managerial career==\n===Coach: Parma and Modena===\nOn 12 November 2012, Crespo announced that he would pursue a career in coaching and would begin work in early July 2013.<ref name=\"november 2012\"/>\n\nHe served as youth coach for the ''Primavera'' team of Parma during the [[2014\u201315 Parma F.C. season|2014\u201315 season]]. After the disbandment of Parma, on 30 June 2015, Crespo was announced as the new manager of [[Serie B]] club [[Modena F.C.|Modena]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.modenafc.net/news/dalla-societo/item/2327-crespo-e-il-nuovo-allenatore-del-modena |publisher=Modena FC |language=Italian |accessdate=30 June 2015 |date=30 June 2015 |title=CRESPO E' IL NUOVO ALLENATORE DEL MODENA |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304125951/http://www.modenafc.net/news/dalla-societo/item/2327-crespo-e-il-nuovo-allenatore-del-modena |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was sacked on 26 March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/81918/serie-b-modena-sack-crespo|title=Serie B: Modena sack Crespo|publisher=Football Italia|date=26 March 2016|accessdate=27 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Back to Parma===\nOn 22 June 2017, Chinese businessman [[Jiang Lizhang]] bought 60% of the stocks of Parma, and assigned Crespo as the new vice president of the club. He worked for Jiang's company Desport as a technical adviser beforehand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/5175615-ex-argentina-chelsea-star-hernan-crespo-reunited-with-former-club-parma-as-vice-president |publisher=Elvin Mensah |date=22 June 2017| title=Ex-Argentina & Chelsea Star Hernan Crespo Reunited With Former Club Parma as Vice-President }}</ref>\n\nOn 2 January 2018, with the club opting to remove the figure of vice-president from its board, Crespo was named new club ambassador.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://parma.repubblica.it/sport/2018/01/02/news/parma_calcio_1913_crespo_da_vicepresidente_ad_ambasciatore_del_club-185668830/ |newspaper=La Repubblica |date=2 January 2018 | title=Parma Calcio 1913: Crespo da vicepresidente ad ambasciatore del club |language=Italian }}</ref>\n\n===Banfield===\nOn 19 December 2018, Crespo was appointed manager of [[Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] side [[Club Atl\u00e9tico Banfield|Banfield]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.soydebanfield.com.ar/Noticia/Contenido/32252 |publisher=Club Atl\u00e9tico Banfield |date=19 December 2018 | title=\"Queremos una identidad que sea marca registrada en Banfield\" |language=Spanish }}</ref>\n\n===Defensa y Justicia===\nOn 25 January 2020, Crespo was appointed manager of [[Defensa y Justicia]], still in the Argentine top tier.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mundod.lavoz.com.ar/futbol/hernan-crespo-es-el-nuevo-dt-de-defensa-y-justicia|title=Hern\u00e1n Crespo es el nuevo DT de Defensa y Justicia|trans-title=Hern\u00e1n Crespo is the new manager of Defensa y Justicia|publisher=Mundo D|language=es|date=25 January 2020|accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn May 2005, Crespo married [[Equestrianism|equestrian]] Alessia Andra Rossi, with whom he has three children. She is half Italian and half Romanian.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.calcionews24.com/crespo-amichevole-in-romania-237954/| title=Crespo, amichevole in Romania? |publisher=calcionews24.com |language=Italian | date=30 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://adevarul.ro/economie/investitii/crespo-convins-soacra-investeasca-romania-1_50ae672e7c42d5a6639c6547/index.html| title=Crespo, convins de soacr\u0103 s\u0103 investeasc\u0103 \u00een Rom\u00e2nia |publisher=adevarul.ro |language=Romanian | date=30 May 2012|accessdate=10 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.sky.it/sport/statistiche/calcio/2010_2011/serie_a/giocatori/parma/hernan_jorge_crespo.html#calciatori|title=>Hernan Jorge Crespo \u2013 Statistiche, informazioni e storia \u2013 Sport \u2013 Sky.it|accessdate=23 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304042547/http://sport.sky.it/sport/statistiche/calcio/2010_2011/serie_a/giocatori/parma/hernan_jorge_crespo.html#calciatori|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n! colspan=\"3\" |League\n!colspan=2|Cup\n!colspan=2|League Cup\n!colspan=2|Continental\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n| rowspan=4|[[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]\n|[[1993\u201394 Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|1993\u201394]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]\n||25||16||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||28||16\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|1994\u201395]]\n||18||4||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||6\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n|1995\u201396]]\n||21||4||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||13||10||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||34||14\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Total\n!64!!24!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!20!!12!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!84!!36\n|-\n| rowspan=5|[[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]\n|[[1996\u201397 Serie A|1996\u201397]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[Serie A]]\n||27||12||1||0|